Intuition
so for optimal solution we use 2 pointers in which we calculate lmax and rmax directly , we know water stored = min(lmax, rmax) - height[i] .
Since trapped water depends on the smaller boundary, if left_max < right_max, then the water on the left side is already determined by left_max. The exact future value of right_max doesn't matter because it is already taller. So I process the left side and move left. Similarly, when right_max < left_max, I process the right side. This allows me to avoid storing prefix and suffix arrays and achieve O(1) space.

Approach
so what we are doing is we initalize 2 poniters left and right at start and end of array , we initalize lmax , rmax and ans to zero ,

now we traverse till left pointer meets right pointer
we calculate lmax and rmax at left and right indices

The key observation is:

If left_max < right_max, then the water level on the left side is already determined by left_max.
Since the right boundary is guaranteed to be taller, the exact value of right_max does not matter. We can safely calculate the water trapped at the current left position and move the left pointer inward.
Similarly, if right_max <= left_max, then the water level on the right side is already determined by right_max. We calculate the water trapped at the current right position and move the right pointer inward.

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n)
Space complexity:
O(1)
Code
class Solution:
    def trap(self, height: List[int]) -> int:
        n = len(height)
        ans = 0
        left = 0 
        right = n - 1
        lmax = rmax = 0

        while left < right:
            lmax = max(lmax , height[left])
            rmax = max(rmax , height[right])

            if lmax < rmax:
                ans += lmax - height[left]
                left += 1
            else:
                ans += rmax - height[right]
                right -= 1
        return ans
